His Romanae vetusta-tis Ἐναρ- menta in Auqusta Vindelicorum et eius diocesi, Augsburg, Ratdolt, 1505, was the first attempt to deal with Roman inscriptions in Germany3 and he is also credited by Zasius with a profound knowledge of Roman law.
